This may be explained by the following considerations. ‘Clustering’ the positive patients increases the risk of colonization for the caregivers who look after them. As Fig. 2
shows, in the case of strict spatial cohorting with no personnel cohorting applied, a high number of health-care workers became colonized during the day. As a result, if during the shift the caregivers were required to visit both positive and negative patients, the infection would spread faster within the ward (see Fig. 3
).
